00:37:46.320 --> 00:37:47.620
&gt;&gt; Sy Montgomery: Oh, good, go.

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:49.200
&gt;&gt; Juli Berwald: So I went
and talked to so robotic,

00:37:49.200 --> 00:37:51.690
some people making
robotic jellyfish.

00:37:51.690 --> 00:37:54.670
And this is really one of my
favorite stories in the book.

00:37:54.670 --> 00:38:00.260
But by trying to make jellyfish
robots, they discovered

00:38:00.260 --> 00:38:03.840
that it's not the
push of the jellyfish

00:38:03.840 --> 00:38:05.140
that makes it go forward.

00:38:05.140 --> 00:38:07.470
It's actually that
peplum, the flap,

00:38:07.470 --> 00:38:09.460
the very pretty part
of the jelly.

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:11.270
It doesn't have any
muscles in it.

00:38:11.270 --> 00:38:15.000
But just the movement of it
is actually what drives the

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:16.660
jellyfish forward
through the water.

00:38:16.660 --> 00:38:18.830
And what they later
discovered is

00:38:18.830 --> 00:38:21.770
that the wiggle creates
these turbulent eddies

00:38:21.770 --> 00:38:24.720
that create a low pressure
system in front of the animal.

00:38:24.720 --> 00:38:27.400
So jellyfish are actually
sucking themselves

00:38:27.400 --> 00:38:28.700
through the water.

00:38:28.700 --> 00:38:30.450
Like if you take a breath, yeah.

00:38:30.450 --> 00:38:32.620
And if you start looking
around in the ocean,

00:38:32.620 --> 00:38:35.470
you start noticing how
does everything swim?

00:38:35.470 --> 00:38:36.770
Well, they all wiggle.

00:38:36.770 --> 00:38:38.070
Everything wiggles.

00:38:38.070 --> 00:38:41.590
And the reason for that wiggle
is to create this low pressure

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:44.730
that pulls marine creatures
and aquatic creatures

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:46.420
through the water
rather than pushes.

00:38:46.420 --> 00:38:48.990
And we're so, you know,
we're so terrestrial.

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:51.480
When we walk, we push back
on the ground behind us.

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:53.770
But that's not what
goes not in the ocean.

00:38:53.770 --> 00:38:56.340
So extraordinary discovery.

00:38:56.340 --> 00:38:59.180
And it came from looking
at jellyfish swimming.

