did not find anything

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:35.420
with jellyfish and music.

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:37.470
But it's a great question.

00:45:37.470 --> 00:45:44.880
I know they can sense currents.

00:45:44.880 --> 00:45:48.250
And it's, oh, I do
have one story.

00:45:48.250 --> 00:45:51.130
Yeah. When the jellyfish
stinging cell,

00:45:51.130 --> 00:45:55.980
the stinging cell actually has
hair cells just like inside

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:59.650
of our ears as a
trigger mechanism.

00:45:59.650 --> 00:46:03.470
And they listen for the
buzz of a zooplankton.

00:46:03.470 --> 00:46:05.260
Which would be like
the buzz of a fly.

00:46:05.260 --> 00:46:06.560
&gt;&gt; Sy Montgomery: Oh, my gosh.

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:08.640
&gt;&gt; Juli Berwald: And if
it's the correct frequency.

00:46:08.640 --> 00:46:11.510
And they can also have these,
there's these sugar sensors

00:46:11.510 --> 00:46:13.660
that smell like zooplankton
are kind of like pigpen.

00:46:13.660 --> 00:46:15.150
They give off all these sugars.

00:46:15.150 --> 00:46:17.170
And so, if it senses
both the sugars

00:46:17.170 --> 00:46:20.510
and the correct frequency,
then it will trigger the cell.

00:46:20.510 --> 00:46:23.260
And then it gets even crazier.

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:27.180
They also have a sensor
that smells proline.

00:46:27.180 --> 00:46:29.100
Which is in crustacean blood.

00:46:29.100 --> 00:46:32.230
And they twist those hair cells

00:46:32.230 --> 00:46:35.220
so that they detect
a higher frequency.

00:46:35.220 --> 00:46:39.500
And if they smell, it's
like hitting a zooplankton.

00:46:39.500 --> 00:46:42.550
It will panic, and it will
buzz at a higher frequency.

00:46:42.550 --> 00:46:43.850
And its blood will
be in the water.

00:46:43.850 --> 00:46:47.110
It will send off a second
battery of stinging cells.

00:46:47.110 --> 00:46:51.410
So, and they've actually, the
jellyfish have repair proteins

00:46:51.410 --> 00:46:54.110
to fix those hair cells
on their stinging cells

00:46:54.110 --> 00:46:55.420
if they are disrupted.

00:46:55.420 --> 00:46:57.980
In our cochlea we
don't have them.

00:46:57.980 --> 00:47:00.790
Which is why, when we hear
loud noises, we can go deaf.

00:47:00.790 --> 00:47:05.790
And they have extracted
those repair proteins from,

00:47:05.790 --> 00:47:07.320
actually from sea anemones.

00:47:07.320 --> 00:47:08.770
Which are easier
to grow in the lab.

00:47:08.770 --> 00:47:11.780
And applied them to
damaged mouse cochlea.

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:14.460
And it repaired the hair
proteins in the cochlea.

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:17.490
So they're looking at it
as, more for military.

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:19.220
Like if you're around
a big explosion,

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:20.990
they are could get
this, repair proteins

00:47:20.990 --> 00:47:23.230
in your inner ear
and fix that up.

00:47:23.230 --> 00:47:26.450
So, yeah, that's the only sound

00:47:26.450 --> 00:47:29.180
and jellyfish answer
I have, but.

00:47:29.180 --> 00:47:30.480
&gt;&gt; Linda Holmes: Yeah,

00:47:30.480 --> 00:47:31.780
sounds like they have
everything they need

00:47:31.780 --> 00:47:33.080
